<p id=3D"GUID-5EB69231-DABD-4EE2-826D-ADDEBE36F6C9"> Quantile-quantile (QQ)=
 plots are an exploratory tool used to assess the similarity between the di=
stribution of one numeric variable and a normal distribution, or between th=
e distributions of two numeric variables.</p><p id=3D"GUID-8CE4A6E0-4116-49=
7C-9144-B966CAAB0D47">There are two types of QQ plots, normal QQ plots and =
general QQ plots. </p><ul purpose=3D"ul" id=3D"UL_6DAFB0EE21E14CF3951E44CD1=
6BB067A"><li purpose=3D"li" id=3D"LI_A749B85A8C6C491495E7627A888C6DBA">Norm=
al QQ plots are constructed by plotting the quantiles of a numeric variable=
 against the quantiles of a normal distribution.</li><li purpose=3D"li" id=
=3D"LI_90207572739E43DA9DC9BCB3B9B413CC">General QQ plots plot the quantile=
s of one numeric variable against the quantiles of a second numeric variabl=
e.</li></ul><p></p><p id=3D"GUID-99329BFD-FCB3-43BA-A31F-ECB92FCA8AB9">If t=
he distributions of the compared quantiles are identical, the plotted point=
s will form a straight 45-degree line. The farther the plotted points devia=
te from a straight line, the less similar the compared distributions.</p><s=
ection class=3D"section1 padded-anchor" id=3D"GUID-49B3C4A8-D0D6-4CF1-95A2-=
2A93E22B1F6A" purpose=3D"section1"><h2>Variables
</h2><p id=3D"GUID-D821931F-E011-4726-9F78-36D94FA79047">Normal QQ plots re=
quire one numeric variable that will be plotted against a normal distributi=
on. General QQ plots require two numeric variables that will be plotted aga=
inst each other.</p></section><section class=3D"section1 padded-anchor" id=
=3D"ESRI_SECTION1_34DC6192FE7F4D9496A3000A9F081617" purpose=3D"section1"><h=
2>Transformation</h2><p id=3D"GUID-A4549209-BE55-4FF4-AB6F-24DD472A604B">So=
me analytical methods require that data be normally distributed. When the d=
ata is skewed (the distribution is lopsided), you might want to transform t=
he data to make it normal. Normal QQ plots allow you to explore the effects=
 of logarithmic and square root transformations on the distribution of your=
 data while comparing them to a normal distribution.</p><section class=3D"s=
ection2 padded-anchor" id=3D"ESRI_SECTION2_2F09AAC5A35347A4B7A43D3B1AE4D988=
" purpose=3D"section2"><h3>Logarithmic transformation</h3><p id=3D"GUID-68A=
E11AA-3ADB-44F4-BD4E-13980F1D3071"> The logarithmic transformation is often=
 used where the data has a positively skewed distribution and there are a f=
ew very large values. If these large values are located in your dataset, th=
e log transformation will help make the variances more constant and normali=
ze your data.</p><div class=3D"panel trailer-1 note" id=3D"GUID-19B3345A-33=
1F-426D-9864-C7BD65B7F8FA"><h5 class=3D"icon-ui-comment trailer-0">Note:</h=
5><p id=3D"GUID-DDDA3E20-483B-46AF-BEFD-4DECB743D16F">Logarithmic transform=
ations can only be applied if all of the variable's values are greater than=
 zero. Any values of zero will result in an error. </p></div></section><sec=
tion class=3D"section2 padded-anchor" id=3D"ESRI_SECTION2_8C103A35D50B466AB=
D21F88B705FF7B3" purpose=3D"section2"><h3>Square root transformation</h3><p=
 id=3D"GUID-408B4AC2-92DD-4DE7-97D9-4D8CD8BC4485">A square root transformat=
ion is similar to a logarithmic transformation in that it reduces right ske=
wness of a dataset. Unlike logarithmic transformations, square root transfo=
rmations can be applied to zero.</p><div class=3D"panel trailer-1 note" id=
=3D"GUID-CB5E21D0-3E4C-4B7A-B6D6-A0432190F2A1"><h5 class=3D"icon-ui-comment=
 trailer-0">Note:</h5><p id=3D"GUID-284A88D7-85D0-439E-AA40-B3EAE3B8844D">S=
quare root transformations can only be applied if all the variable's values=
 are greater than or equal to zero. Any negative values will result in an e=
rror.</p></div></section><section class=3D"section2 padded-anchor" id=3D"ES=
RI_SECTION2_AA745C6D14D24A74A3217874D0F97DA3" purpose=3D"section2"><h3>Inve=
rse</h3><p id=3D"GUID-E2D5096B-DAAD-41BE-9EA6-9531D5E72A97">An inverse tran=
sformation takes the reciprocal (1/x) of each value (x) in the field.  </p>=
<div class=3D"panel trailer-1 note" id=3D"GUID-2AD4EE1A-7F92-487D-952A-44EC=
7F989668"><h5 class=3D"icon-ui-comment trailer-0">Note:</h5><p id=3D"GUID-D=
1017826-9200-4622-8444-C30BBEC2444E">Inverse transformations cannot be appl=
ied to zero values.  If there are zero values in the field, they are treate=
d as null.</p></div></section><section class=3D"section2 padded-anchor" id=
=3D"ESRI_SECTION2_7D8AF6952CC94F4CAF242275C9025EB6" purpose=3D"section2"><h=
3>Box-Cox</h3><p id=3D"GUID-64F3EC8B-D37E-44B0-AEC1-10550D6D1F73">A Box-Cox=
 transformation applies the following power function to normally distribute=
 values:</p><p id=3D"GUID-DFA857DA-30CC-4FA2-A9E5-01883EF8362B"></p><figure=
 class=3D"fig" href=3D"#"><img src=3D"https://doc.arcgis.com/en/allsource/1=
.0/analysis/charts/GUID-B45DE0FA-7B71-4706-8020-0C69259DF64A-web.png" alt=
=3D"Box-Cox transformation" title=3D"Box-Cox transformation" loading=3D"laz=
y"></figure>where <i>x'</i> is the transformed value, <i>x</i> is the origi=
nal value, <i> =CE=BB<sub>1</sub></i> is the <span class=3D"uicontrol">Powe=
r</span> parameter, and  <i>=CE=BB<sub>2</sub></i> is the <span class=3D"ui=
control">Shift</span> parameter.<p></p><div class=3D"panel trailer-1 note" =
id=3D"GUID-24B7EA28-7EE4-4435-A5D4-509A7966956E"><h5 class=3D"icon-ui-comme=
nt trailer-0">Note:</h5><p id=3D"GUID-BB9E2E96-41E3-42BA-811C-B639C37FF5A7"=
>Box-Cox transformations can only be applied to positive values.  In cases =
where negative or zero values exist, use  the <span class=3D"uicontrol">Shi=
ft</span> parameter to ensure all values are positive. </p></div></section>=
</section><section class=3D"section1 padded-anchor" id=3D"ESRI_SECTION1_F42=
666EC88124302BC9FFD38C2648629" purpose=3D"section1"><h2>Axes</h2><section c=
lass=3D"section2 padded-anchor" id=3D"ESRI_SECTION2_5A2E887CF16C4687A44995F=
C5E5684E8" purpose=3D"section2"><h3>Axis bounds</h3><p id=3D"GUID-D67B48FD-=
3885-4587-8060-4BCDD670089A">Default minimum and maximum axis bounds are se=
t based on the range of data values represented on the axis. These values c=
an be customized by typing a new desired axis bound value. Clicking the res=
et icon will revert the axis bound to the default value.</p></section><sect=
ion class=3D"section2 padded-anchor" id=3D"ESRI_SECTION2_E7E52F03FE0E46EA98=
D77DD725A575BA" purpose=3D"section2"><h3>Number format</h3><p id=3D"GUID-F7=
9A7D71-45FE-4B2F-8A1B-D60840C0806C">You can format the way an axis will dis=
play numeric values by specifying a number format category or by defining  =
a custom format string.</p></section></section><section class=3D"section1 p=
added-anchor" id=3D"ESRI_SECTION1_6AA04A8DAB18468A920106EE12411AA8" purpose=
=3D"section1"><h2>Appearance</h2><section class=3D"section2 padded-anchor" =
id=3D"GUID-D56B578F-EA28-4610-8F00-5BF25A0F4CDD" purpose=3D"section2"><h3>T=
itles and description</h3><p id=3D"GUID-5270241D-8D11-446A-91DA-FBB8D9E3E84=
E"> Charts and axes are given default titles based on the variable names an=
d chart type. These can be edited on the <span class=3D"uicontrol">General<=
/span> tab in the <span class=3D"uicontrol">Chart Properties</span> pane. Y=
ou can also provide a chart <span class=3D"uicontrol">Description</span>, w=
hich is a block of text that appears at the bottom of the chart window.</p>=
</section><section class=3D"section2 padded-anchor" id=3D"ESRI_SECTION2_A40=
207E88D014D8398B9FE179923E690" purpose=3D"section2"><h3>Color</h3><p id=3D"=
GUID-0B2BCB86-52B7-4A3B-AEDA-CCA20976FAF7"> QQ plots inherit their outline =
and fill colors from the source layer symbology. By symbolizing a layer wit=
h a different attribute than either of the QQ plot variables, a third varia=
ble can be shown on the QQ plot visualization.</p></section></section><sect=
ion class=3D"section1 padded-anchor" id=3D"GUID-D9F82C3A-1001-4A65-AF45-EAE=
260CF12AE" purpose=3D"section1"><h2>Guides</h2><p id=3D"GUID-9573CBFC-B111-=
4263-B75A-AABBDC54A065">Guide lines or ranges can be added to charts as a r=
eference or way to highlight significant values. To add a new guide, on the=
 <span class=3D"uicontrol">Guides</span> tab in the <span class=3D"uicontro=
l">Chart Properties</span> pane, click <span class=3D"uicontrol">Add guide<=
/span>. To draw a line, enter a <span class=3D"uicontrol">Value</span> wher=
e you want the line to draw. To create a range, enter a <span class=3D"uico=
ntrol">to</span> value. You can optionally add text to your guide by specif=
ying a <span class=3D"uicontrol">Label</span>.</p></section><section class=
=3D"section1 padded-anchor" id=3D"ESRI_SECTION1_7C74E8F713CF449292E1B825B99=
9A0DF" purpose=3D"section1"><h2>Example</h2><p id=3D"GUID-CEF75A20-F7A7-4DC=
7-B64C-4BB485352344">Create a QQ plot to evaluate whether particulate matte=
r samples in California are normally distributed. </p><ul purpose=3D"ul" id=
=3D"UL_8516096A96C7443A853CC70185D91B5C"><li purpose=3D"li" id=3D"LI_CF86A1=
922C064B399E4606573168F3B5"><span class=3D"uicontrol">Compare the distribut=
ion of</span>=E2=80=94<span class=3D"usertext">Particulate Matter</span></l=
i><li purpose=3D"li" id=3D"LI_7BD8135070EB4F849525786D298C9686"><span class=
=3D"uicontrol">With transformation</span>=E2=80=94<span class=3D"uicontrol"=
>None</span></li><li purpose=3D"li" id=3D"LI_2A6357FA9E54412095D9E4EEF79508=
BC"><span class=3D"uicontrol">To</span>=E2=80=94<span class=3D"uicontrol">&=
lt;Normal Distribution&gt;</span></li></ul><img purpose=3D"img" placement=
=3D"inline" alt=3D"QQ plot" title=3D"QQ plot" src=3D"https://doc.arcgis.com=
/en/allsource/1.0/analysis/charts/GUID-EEFD3CC1-D1CF-4C6E-8AD3-DDFC551F58F2=
-web.png" loading=3D"lazy"></section>
